ontigny-en-Ostervent, Noorderdepartement, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrijk","Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Hauts de France, Nord, France":"Noorderdepartement, Hauts-de-France, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1229–1292":"1229–1292","1235–1284":"1235–1284","1252–1309":"1252–1309","1205–1267":"1205–1267","1201–1268":"1201–1268","1205":"1205","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","1201":"1201","1252":"1252","1284":"1284","1309":"1309","1292":"1292","1229":"1229","Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France":"Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France","Montigny-en-Ostervent, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Montigny-en-Ostervent, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Hauts de France, Nord, France":"Nord, Hauts-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Montigny","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Henri, Jacques, Normand, Remi.","French: habitational name from (Le) Montigny, the name of several places in various parts of France (from a Gallo-Roman estate name, <i>Montiniacum</i>, formed either from a personal name or from a derivative of <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>). Compare   Demontigny  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Demontigny","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aurele, Gilles, Jacques.","French: habitational name, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, for someone from any of several places in various parts of France named Montigny (see   Montigny  )."]}]},{"name":"en","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 任, based on its Mandarin pronunciation, see   Ren   1.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 全, based on its pronunciation in Shanghai dialect, see   Quan   2.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 曾, see   Zeng  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ren","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Yong, Hong, Hui, Chuan, Gang, Guang, Jian, Liang, Lihua, Ning, Qing, Chang, Min, Shen, Yiming.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 任, a term for women's rank of peerage in ancient Chinese: (i) it is said that the surname can be traced back to one of the 25 sons of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). (ii) from Ren (任), the name of an ancient state (located in Renxian in Hebei province) granted to Yu Yang, said to be a son or grandson of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). His descendants adopted the name of the state as their surname. (iii) from Ren (任), the name of a state (located in Shandong province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","English: variant of   Renn   2."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert II de Montigny en Ostrevent was born in 1229, in Montigny-en-Ostervent, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, his father, Eustache III de Montigny en Ostrevent, was 24 and his mother, Madeleine de Trith, was 28. He had at least 1 son with Catherine de Thiant. He died in 1292, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1229–1292":"1229–1292","1235–1284":"1235–1284","1252–1309":"1252–1309","1205–1267":"1205–1267","1201–1268":"1201–1268","1205":"1205","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","1201":"1201","1252":"1252","1284":"1284","1309":"1309","1292":"1292","1229":"1229","Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France":"Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Nord, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Montigny-en-Ostervent, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Montigny-en-Ostervent, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Hauts de France, Nord, France":"Nord, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1229–1292":"1229–1292","1235–1284":"1235–1284","1252–1309":"1252–1309","1205–1267":"1205–1267","1201–1268":"1201–1268","1205":"1205","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","1201":"1201","1252":"1252","1284":"1284","1309":"1309","1292":"1292","1229":"1229","Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France":"Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Nord, Hauts-de-France, Ranska","Montigny-en-Oste